-- Cairn India Raises 22.5 Billion Rupees by Selling Bonds for First Time
-- B y   R a k t e e m   K a t a k e y
-- 2010-10-11T11:28:21Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-11/cairn-india-plans-to-raise-22-5-billion-rupees-selling-bonds-data-shows.html
Cairn India Ltd. , which operates the
nation’s biggest onshore oilfield, raised 22.5 billion rupees
($507 million) by selling bonds for the first time, according to
data compiled by Bloomberg.  The oil explorer sold a combined 12.5 billion rupees in two
equal parts, maturing in July 2012 and October 2012 and paying
coupons of 8.35 percent and 8.4 percent respectively, the data
show. A 10 billion rupee portion of variable rate bonds due
January 2013 was also sold, according to the data.  Cairn India produces about 125,000 barrels of crude oil a
day from its fields in Rajasthan state, parent  Cairn Energy Plc 
said in a statement Aug. 16. In March, the company raised its
output target from the site to 240,000 barrels. Cairn India
found oil and gas in the Nagayalanka-1Z well from an onshore
site in the Krishna-Godavari basin, it said in a statement to
the Bombay Stock Exchange Aug. 23.  Manu Kapoor, a spokesman at Cairn India, based in Gurgaon,
near New Delhi, declined to comment when contacted on his mobile
phone.  Cairn India has 111.1 billion rupees in loans maturing by
end-2016, according to  data  compiled by Bloomberg.  Cairn Energy said Aug. 16 it aims to sell a majority stake
of its Indian unit to Vedanta Resources Plc. The planned sale is
still awaiting regulatory approval, Cairn Energy Chief Executive
Officer Bill Gammell told reporters in Mumbai today.  Cairn India  shares, which have gained 22 percent this year,
climbed 2.4 percent to 344.60 rupees at close of trading in
Mumbai today. The Bombay Stock Exchange’s benchmark  Sensitive
Index  rose 0.4 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
